resourceAbstractObject.default: All the data stored in this collection of datasets was collected during the period 2019-2023 within the framework of the project number ANR-19-CE32-0005 entitled "Impacts of Microclimatic Processes on foRest bIodiversity redistributioN under macroclimaTe warming" (IMPRINT) funded by the Agence nationale de la recherche (ANR). The project aims to model forest microclimates at fine spatiotemporal resolution and link it to understory biodiversity data. The different datasets available in that collection contain (i) biodiversity surveys (vascular plants, bryophytes and soil artropods), (ii) in-situ microclimate records (both air and soil temperature near the ground surface), (iii) ground-truth measurements of stand characteristics (maximum height, stem diameter, species identity and status) and (iv) high-resolution airborne LiDAR images, all collected across three deciduous state forests in France (Aigoual, Blois and Mormal). Mormal is a lowland forest dominated by beech (Fagus sylvatica) and/or pedunculate oak (Quercus robur) stands, Blois is a lowland forest dominated by pure sessile oak stands (Quercus petraea), and Aigoual is a mountain forest dominated by pure beech stands. All three are state forests managed by the ONF (Office National des Forêts, i.e. French forest office), mostly as even-aged “high forests”, except for a few coppices in Aigoual as well as some stands not managed for accessibility or conservation reasons.

resourceAbstractObject.default:
Data from the ANR IMPRINT Project (2019-2023) : floristic inventories of each plot (60) of Blois forest :

Floristic surveys were conducted during the vegetative season, from the 17th to the 25th of May 2021, on a 400 m² surface around the central sensors of each plot. Species presence and abundance are recorded separately in each vertical strata: mosses, herbaceous, lower shrub, higher shrub, and tree (see more detail below).

resourceAbstractObject.default:
Data from the ANR IMPRINT Project (2019-2023) : describing each plot (n = 60) of the domanial forest of Blois.
General information at the plot scale : some information is calculated on a GIS software (coordinates, elevation, slope, aspect, northness, or Topographic Wetness Index are calculated from a digital elevation model, and distance between the plot and the edge of the forest, or distance between the plot and the nearest river from IGN data), some information is visually estimated in the field (e.g. stand structure, cover of woody debris, rocks, silvicultural path), and lastly, some information is measured from field samples (soil pH).

resourceAbstractObject.default:
Data from the ANR IMPRINT Project (2019-2023) : LiDAR coverage of Aigoual forest was carried out the 18th July 2021.

From this high-density airborne LiDAR, we obtained:

- A classified LiDAR Point cloud. We hereby share a sample of this point cloud, representing a 20 m buffer around each of our 60 plots in Aigoual forest.

- A table of structural metrics extracted for each plot from the LiDAR point cloud, calculated on different buffer sizes from 1 to 100 meters. 

These data can be joined to the spatial data Aigoual_plots, and tree or biodiversity data by the id_plot.

resourceAbstractObject.default:
Data from the ANR IMPRINT Project (2019-2023) : temperature time series of each plot (60) of the domanial forest of Aigoual :
Two HOBO sensors were placed at the center of each of 60 plots, to measure air temperature (1 m above the ground ; every hour), and soil temperature (8 cm below the ground ; every two hours).
This dataset is a compilation of all soil and air temperatures measured by HOBO sensors in each plot.
The time series ranges from July 31, 2020 to September 19, 2023, although not all plots have data on this complete temporal range.

resourceAbstractObject.default:
Data from the ANR IMPRINT Project (2019-2023) : LiDAR coverage of Blois forest was carried out the 17th June 2021.

From this high-density airborne LiDAR, we obtained:

- A classified LiDAR Point cloud. We hereby share a sample of this point cloud, representing a 20 m buffer around each of our 60 plots in Blois forest.

- A table of structural metrics extracted for each plot from the LiDAR point cloud, calculated on different buffer sizes from 1 to 100 meters. 

These data can be joined to the spatial data Blois_plots, and tree or biodiversity data by the id_plot.

resourceAbstractObject.default:
Data from the ANR IMPRINT Project (2019-2023) : temperature time series of each plot (60) of the domanial forest of Blois :
Two HOBO sensors were placed at the center of each of 60 plots, to measure air temperature (1 m above the ground ; every hour), and soil temperature (8 cm below the ground ; every two hours).
This dataset is a compilation of all soil and air temperatures measured by HOBO sensors in each plot.
The time series ranges from July 11, 2020 to August 28, 2023, although not all plots have data on this complete temporal range.
